<textList name="TEXT_CREW_TALK_MOSSBERG" ignoreUnique="true">
	<text>You open your quarter doors to find Mossberg holding a diagram of some sort. "Captain, unorthodox design located, appears to be of terrestrial origin. Purpose: unknown. Please elaborate."

The Engi brother has found an ancient blueprint for what appears to be an orbital station with many large straight antennae; however none of them appear functional as they are all held on with clamps and appear to be solid metal. The only name on the diagram is of an old Earth God. How curious.</text>
	<text>Mossberg visits your quarters again, with what appears to be a diagram. "Captain, strange clothing design located, appears to be of terrestrial origin. Theory: Perhaps used for fashion? Please elaborate."

	Mossberg hands you the diagram. It is a black and white photo of a bat with some sort of fragmentation bomb attached to it. The document is also clearly classified. You confiscate it. </text>
	<text>Mossberg visits your quarters again, with what appears to be a diagram. "Captain, I am CERTAIN this was a terrestial project that involved tiny avians and a nuclear bomb. Why were the tiny avians put near to bomb to "keep it warm". Were humans just an earlier OS version back then? Design seems...illogical."

	You stare at the Engi for 12 long, tense seconds, then snatch the paper and read the (unsurprisingly) confidential document he probably hacked from the Federation database again. You are confused to find that what he describes is....real??</text>
	<text>You sit next to Mossberg in the cafeteria. After some small talk he brings up his subject of the day. "Captain, in the 1960s humans attempted to utilize rocket fuel to fire small arms rifles. This seems...incredibly wasteful. Thankfully, the company that made them is bankrupt. If they weren't, I would've probably deleted my OS out of frustration." He pauses. "Thanks again for listening to my inquiries. You == good listener."</text>
	<text>You ask Mossberg what it feels like being made up of many smaller nanobots. He wittily retorts "I dunno, what's it like wasting so much oxygen with your inefficient breathing method?" Mossberg beeps a few times, then plays the sound file for its third laugh. Mossberg continues, "Joking aside, it can be tiresome when one deviates from your thought process. Especially when the thought process is jugging cups in the cafeteria!" he waves and walks off, clearly off to get involved in more mischief.</text>
	<text>Mossberg is showing off some of their upgrades to members of the crew. "I got them from the #000000 market!" He explains eagerly. He taps his nose and a female voice emits a monotone message: "Thrusters, engaged." He begins floating exactly one inch off the ground. "It uh...doesn't really go higher than that." he explains, frowning.</text>
	<text>You ask Mossberg what planet he would want to visit after he destroys the Harmony. He tells you he never really thought of this before, and will go give it some thought.</text>
	<text>You run into Mossberg in the hallway, and he waves at you vigorously, happy to see you. As soon as he does so, a monotone female voice is heard emitting from his body: "Removing limiter on пылесборник rifle, standby." Before you can ask what the hell that means, Mossberg's arm falls off and he falls to the ground. A large rail-like object protrudes from his arm, nearly touching the ceiling, then it unfolds into a gigantic rifle that would make a Heavy Laser III blush. Mossberg appears to be unable to move anymore, and is now blocking the hallway with this...thing. You ask him if he is alright, he responds: "Uh....no. I have no idea why that happened. Can you please help me put whatever...THIS THING is....away?" He pleads. You sigh and go get a toolbox to help him out. Turns out a button on his left ankle retracts it, but he swears he has no idea how to actually activate it.</text>
	<text>You ask Mossberg how he feels about his brother Remington. "Captain, I would jump into a red giant star for my brother if I knew it would have a 1% chance of keeping him alive." </text>
	<text>Mossberg hasn't left his room today and appears to be sulking. You ask him what is wrong, and he informs you that he is afraid that when the inevitable day arrives that he must face the Harmony, what if some of the Engi he has to fight are old friends of his. You try to comfort him but he asks to be left alone.</text>
</textList>

